      <p class="key-stat-txt">reduction in inflammatory acne lesions with oral zinc supplementation. A meta-analysis in <em>Dermatologic Therapy</em> found that <strong>30-50mg of elemental zinc daily for 12 weeks significantly reduced inflammatory acne</strong> through anti-inflammatory, antibacterial, sebum-regulating, and wound-healing mechanisms. Zinc is the single most evidence-backed oral supplement for acne.</p>
    </div>

    <p>The gut-skin axis — the bidirectional communication between the gastrointestinal microbiome and skin health — has emerged as a critical factor in acne pathogenesis. Gut dysbiosis (imbalanced intestinal bacteria) increases intestinal permeability, allowing bacterial endotoxins (lipopolysaccharides) into the bloodstream. These endotoxins trigger systemic inflammation that manifests in the skin as acne, rosacea, and eczema. Oral probiotics (specifically Lactobacillus and Bifidobacterium strains) restore gut microbial balance, reduce intestinal permeability, and decrease the circulating inflammatory mediators that drive skin inflammation. A 2023 systematic review confirmed that oral probiotics significantly reduce acne severity scores over 8-12 weeks.</p>

    <p>The third internal pillar is hormonal sebum regulation. Excess sebum production — driven by testosterone-to-DHT conversion via 5-alpha-reductase — creates the oily, pore-clogging environment that C. acnes bacteria thrive in. Zinc inhibits 5-alpha-reductase activity, reducing DHT-driven sebum overproduction. Vitamin A (retinol/retinoids) normalizes keratinocyte turnover, preventing the dead skin cell accumulation that combines with excess sebum to clog pores. Together, zinc and vitamin A address the hormonal and cellular mechanisms that create acne-favorable conditions.</p>

