    <h2 id="faq">Frequently Asked Questions About Gummies for Acne</h2>
    <details class="fq"><summary>Can gummies actually help with acne?</summary><p>Yes. Zinc (30-50mg) reduces inflammatory acne by 49% per meta-analysis. Probiotics significantly reduce acne severity via gut-skin axis. Vitamin A normalizes keratinocyte turnover. Not a cure for severe cystic acne (requires dermatologist), but meaningful for mild-to-moderate acne.</p></details>
    <details class="fq"><summary>How does zinc help with acne?</summary><p>Four mechanisms: anti-inflammatory (inhibits NF-kB, IL-6), antibacterial (bacteriostatic against C. acnes), sebum regulation (inhibits 5-alpha-reductase/DHT), and wound healing (accelerates repair, reduces scarring). 30-50mg zinc picolinate daily for 12 weeks.</p></details>
    <details class="fq"><summary>What is the gut-skin axis?</summary><p>Bidirectional communication between gut microbiome and skin. Gut dysbiosis increases intestinal permeability, allowing inflammatory LPS into bloodstream, triggering skin inflammation and acne. Probiotics restore balance, reduce permeability, decrease inflammatory markers.</p></details>
    <details class="fq"><summary>How long do acne gummies take to work?</summary><p>Zinc: 2-4 weeks onset, max results at 8-12 weeks. Probiotics: 4-8 weeks for gut remodeling, visible skin improvement at 6-12 weeks. Vitamin A: 4-6 weeks. Commit to 12 weeks minimum. Photograph weekly for objective tracking.</p></details>
    <details class="fq"><summary>Can biotin in gummies make acne worse?</summary><p>Yes. High-dose biotin (2,500-10,000mcg) competes with B5 for absorption. B5 supports sebum regulation and skin barrier. Reduced B5 can increase breakouts (jawline/chin). Choose acne gummies with zero biotin or add 500mg B5 to counterbalance.</p></details>
    <details class="fq"><summary>Should I take acne gummies with my skincare routine?</summary><p>Yes. Gummies address internal factors (inflammation, gut health, mineral deficiency). Topical skincare addresses external factors (bacteria, pore clogging, surface exfoliation). Combine both for comprehensive acne management. Gummies do not replace topical treatments.</p></details>

